# now lets try to predict, by using a simple linear regression model
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
In[8]:
# Lets create a new column 'Next_Close' which will be the 'Close' price of the next day.
data['Next_Close'] = data['Close'].shift(-1)

data_final_model = data.dropna(subset=['Next_Close']).copy() # remove the last row with NaN

# declare the features and target
features = ['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Adj Close', 'Volume']
target = 'Next_Close'

# Split the time series into train and test sets (70% train, 30% test)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(data_final_model[features], data_final_model[target], test_size=0.3, shuffle=False)

# Train a Linear Regression model (LRM)
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the performance of the LRM
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

print(f'LRM Performance:')
print(f'RMSE: {rmse:.2f}')
print(f'R Score: {r2:.4f}')

LRM Performance:
RMSE: 3.53
R Score: 0.9992
